<subSubSection box="[715,1076,2807,2840]" pageId="17" pageNumber="725" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="17.[714,1307,2732,3154]" box="[715,1076,2807,2840]" pageId="17" pageNumber="725">This species is monotypic.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<paragraph blockId="17.[714,1307,2732,3154]" lastBlockId="17.[1369,2576,281,869]" pageId="17" pageNumber="725">
<subSubSection pageId="17" pageNumber="725" type="distribution">
<caption inLine="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="725" startId="17.[715,887,2846,2879]" targetBox="[1719,1723,842,867]" targetPageId="17">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[715,891,2846,2879]" pageId="17" pageNumber="725">Distribution.</emphasis>
SW Philippines, in S Palawan, Bancalan, Matangule, and Balabac Is.
</caption>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="17" pageNumber="725" type="description">Descriptive notes. Head-body mean 200 mm (males) and 199 mm (females), tail mean 161 mm (males) and 156 mm (females); weight mean 257-1 g (males) and 222.5 g (females). Dorsum of the Southern Palawan Tree Squirrel varies from chestnut to light brown, and venter varies from chestnut to dull brown. The Southern Palawan Tree Squirrel is similar to the Northern Palawan Tree Squirrel (S. juvencus) but is more rufous.</subSubSection>
</paragraph>
<subSubSection box="[1371,2298,360,393]" pageId="17" pageNumber="725" type="biology_ecology">
